column168: 20) SEPARATORS & LINER CONTAINING 4 GLASS BOTTLES, EACH BOTTLE CONTAINING 4 LITERS (1.06 GAL.) OF PRODUCT.  1 BOTTLE OUTOF 4 BROKE.  21) BOTTLE CONTAINS 4 LITERS OF PRODUCT.  THE TOTAL WEIGHT OF EACH SHIPPING CARTON IS 68 LBS.  EACH BOTTLE WEIGHED 17 LBS.  25) FRAGILE HANDLE WITH CARE-THIS SIDE UP.  THE CARTON WASDROPPED WHILE UNLOADING TRUCK AND ONE OUT OF 4 BOTTLES BROKE AND MOST OF THE LIQUID SPILLED ON THE CEMENT PARKING APRON. EMPLOYEES WERE CAUTIONED AND WATER SPRAY WAS USED TO REDUCE VAPORS.  THE PRODUCT RAPIDLY EVAPORATED.  THE TERMINAL MANAGER REVEIWED POTENTIAL HAZARDS AND EMERGENCY ACTION FROM GUIDE 55 IN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK.  THE WET CARTON WAS LEFT OUTSIDE UNTIL ALL VAPORS HAD DISPPEARED.  THE CARTON WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE TUCKER, GA TERMINAL AND THE GOODTHREE BOTTLES WERE RESHIPPED BACK TO THE SHIPPER ON A FREE ASTRAY BASIS.  THE LOADERS WERE CAUTIONED TO USE MORE CARE INHANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  IN AS MUCH AS THE PRODUCT IS A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE AND THE SPILLAGE EXCEEDED THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY A CALL WAS MADE TO THE U.S. COAST GUARD NATIONAS RESPONSE CENTER.  THEINCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO DAVID BENSON WHO ASSIGNED IT CASE #15949 AND SAID HE WOULD REPORT IT TO EPA REGION 4.

column168: SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED APPROXIMATELY 0012 HOURS, APRIL 4, 1990 OF A HAZMAT SPILL ABOARD AIRCRAFT 427EX. THE SPILL APPARENTLY OCCURED INFLIGHT. DAYTON CRASH, FIRE AND RESCUE MET THE AIRCRAFT UPON ARRIVAL AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION UNTIL A CONFIRMATION OF THE MATERIAL COULD BE ESTABLISHED. AT FIRST THE SHIPMENT WAS BELIEVED TO BE UN1703 POISON GAS. UNTIL AN ACTUAL CONFIRMATION OF THE MATERIAL COULD BE ESTABLISHED, THE DECISION TO CONTACT THE REGIONAL HAZMAT TEAM WAS MADE. THE REGIONAL HAZMAT TEAM IDENTIFIED THE SHIPMENT TO ACTUALLY BE GASOLINE AS MARKED, AND CLEARED THE MATERIAL CLEAN-UP. A CLEAN-UP AND CONTAINERIZATION OF THE MATERIAL WAS PERFORMED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA FOR EVALUATION BY ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPARTTMENT.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO A 10,000 GALLON, UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK, FOR A TEST OF THE STATIONS TANKS.  HE HAD APPARENTLY CONNECTED THE HOSES WRONG BECAUSE NOTHING WAS REGISTERING ON THE METER DURING DELIVERY.  HE HAD STOPPED THE TEST SO HE COULD CALL FOR PROPER INSTRUCTIONS.  HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK TO RECONECT THE HOSES PROPERLY.  DRIVER CLOSED ALL VALVES ON THE METER SIDE OF THE TRUCK. PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE COUPLING TO CATCH PRODUCT WHILE DISCONNECTING THE HOSES. HE RELEASED ONE SIDE OF THE FITTING TO RELEAVE THE PRESSURE IN THE HOSE.  PRODUCT STARTED DRIPPING INTO THE BUCKET AS PLANNED.  WHEN THIS STOPPED HE PARTIALLY OPENED THE OTHER FASTENER.  EVERYTHING SEEMED NORMAL AND ALL PRESSURE WAS APPARENTLY GONE. THEREFORE, DRIVER OPENED THE FASTENER THE REST TO THE WAY.  AT THIS POINT THE HOSE BLEW OUT OF THE FITTING ANDHISHANDS FROM PRESSURE INSIDE THE TRUCKS COMPARTMENT.  HE REALIZED THAT ONE OF THE VALVES AT THE BOTTOM WAS STILL OPENED, WHICH HE CLOSED IMMEDIATELY.  AT THAT POINT THE SPILL HAD BEEN MADE OF APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS.

column168: ON FRIDAY APRIL 6, 1990, AT 10:00 AM, OUR TRUCK #95 - A 1981 WHITE ROAD BOS S - WAS LOADED WITH 6902 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL FOR DELIVERY TO 2 LOCATIONS IN ROANE COUNTY. UNFORTUNATELY, THE SHOULDER NARR OWED TO ONLY ABOUT 6" NEXT TO A DRIVEWAY CULVERT. THE IMPACT OF HITTING THE CULVERT CAUSED  THE TRAILER TO BOUNCE RIGHT AND T HE REAR WHEELS  DROPPED INTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH ON THE SHOULDER SIDE. WHEN THE TRAILER  WHEELS IMPACTED THE 2ND DRIVEWAY THEY CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND T RAILER TO ROLL OVER ONCE OR TWICE. THE VEHICLE CAME TO REST ACROSS THE HIGHWAY ON ITS SIDE AND DUE TO DAMAGE T O THE LID ON THE 3RD COMPARTMENT PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPILL ONTO THE ROAD AND I NTO THE DRAINAGE DITCH. THE DRIVER HAD TO CLIMB THROUGH THE BROKEN WINDSHIELD SINCE BOTH DOORS WERE CRUSHED AND COULDN'T BE OPENED. HE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL BY AMBULANCE WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR CONTUSIONS TO THE HEAD. 6 STITCHES FOR A CUT NEXT TO HIS EYE AND 5 STITCHES IN HIS LEFT THUMB. DESPITE HIS INJURIES THE DRIVER OBSERVED THE FUEL SPILL FROM THE 3RD COMPAR TMENT LID WHICH WAS SLIGHTLY AJAR. HE USED THE BROKEN EXHAUST STACK AS A WE DGE BETWEEN THE LID AND THE GROUND IN ORDER TO REDUCE THE FLOW OF PRODUCT F ROM THE TANK. WHEN THE BLAIR VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT ARRIVED THEY USED BARS AND STAKES TO EXE RT MORE PRESSURE ON THE LID - HOWEVER. IT COULD NOT BE COMPLETELY STOPPED. AIRLINES THAT CONTROLLED THE UNLOADING VALVES WERE DAMAGED AND PREVENTED OU R DRAINING THE DRAINING THE DIESEL OUT OF THE TANK.

PRODUCT WAS BEING OFF-LOADED  FROM CARGO TANK THROUGH USE OF CUSTOMERS TRAN SFER PUMP AND HOSES. AFTER APPROX ONE HOUR OF OFF-LOADING, A HOSE COUPLING DISCONNECTED FROM THE PLANT FIXED PIPING. APPROX 150 GALS WAS RELEASED BEFORE THE PUMP WAS SHUT OFF AND NECESSARY VAL VES CLOSED. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED  IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND CLEANED UP BY PLAN T PERSONNEL FOR PROPER  DISPOSAL. THE EXACT CAUSE FOR THE HOSE DISCONNECTING HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED. LOCAL A UTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

PRODUCT WAS BEING GRAVITY OFF-LOADED FROM CARGO TANK INTO CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK. NEAR THE COMPLETION OF THE UNLOADING, THE DRIVER WAS ASKED TO CHECK THE TRAILER FOR THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LEFT BEFORE IT WOULD BE EMPTY. AS THE DRIVER STARTED TO CLIMB ONTO THE TANK, PRODUCT BEGAN FLOWING FROM A VENT ON THE CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK. APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OVERFLOWED FROM THE TANK BEFORE THE DRIVER AND PLANT UNLOADER COULD SHUT OFF NECESSARY VALVES TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS THAT THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK WOULD NOT HOLD THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ORDERED. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND CLEANED UP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL BY PLANT PERSONNEL.

column168: DURING OFFLOAD, IT WAS NOTED THAT TWO (2) OF THE PACKAGES WERE WET. ALL FOUR (4) OF THE PACKAGES WERE ISOLATED AND INSPECTED. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ALL FOUR (4) PACKAGES CONTAINED PLASTIC DRUMS WHICH WERE LABELED AS FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS. THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED AS A DANGEROUS GOOD. ALSO THERE WAS NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION PRESENT WITH THE SHIPMENT. LEAKAGE IS BELIEVED TO BE DUE TO A DEFECTIVE FITTING OR CLOSURE ON THE TOP OF THE DRUMS. THE SHIPMENTS WERE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.

ON APRIL 27, 1990 IN A CARGO TANK OF DOT SPECIFICATION MC312 OWNED AND OPER ATED BY ENVIRITE CORP, ENVIRITE TRANSPORTED A SHIPMENT  OF 5149 GALLONS OF WASTE MANIFESTED  AS "RQ WASTE ACID LIQUID, N.O.S., (NITRIC, HYDROFLUORIC) CORROSIVE  MATERIAL" TO THE ENVIRITE'S PERMITTED WASTE  TREATMENT FACILITY IN CANTON. OH. THE SHIPMENT ORIGINATED  FROM WASHINGTON STEEL, WASHINGTON, PA. IN THE NORMAL COURSE OF TRANSPORTATION A PORTION OF THE LADING  WAS REL EASED THROUGH THE CARGO TANK'S RUPTURE DISK. THE DISCHARGE OCCURED  AT APPR OXIMATELY 11:25AM AT EMPIRE, OHIO ON STATE ROUTE 7 NORTH AT STATE ROUTE 152 INTERCHANGE - APPROX 11 MILES NORHT OF STEUBENVILLE IN JEFFERSON COUNTY. IT APPEARS THAT WHILE IN TRANSIT THE WASTE MATERIAL GENERATED GAS IN SUFFIC IENT QUANTITY TO CAUSE THE RUPTURE DISK TO BREACH. THE RUPTURE DISK, DESIGN ED  TO BURST  AT 50 PSI OF PRESSURE, APPARENTLY FUNCTIONED  PROPERLY. WHEN THE DISK RUPTURED, THE LADING DISCHARGED  FROM THE OPENING AND SPRAYED  ONT O THE PASSING LANE FOR APPROX 1/10TH MILE. APPROX 51 GALLONS OF LADING WERE RELEASED. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE CANTON ENVIRITE FACILITY AND INFORMED PLA NT AUTHORITIES OF THE SPILL. HE INDICATED SINCE THAT THE WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE 90 DEGREES AND SUN, THE SPRAYED MATERIAL HAD DRIED  ON THE ROADWAY A ND BERM WITHIN 15MINS. BASED ON THE DRIVER'S DESCRIPTION OF THE SITE AND OU R KNOWLEDGE  OF THE WASTE, OUR EVALUATION OF THE SITUATION WAS THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE DANGER TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR HUMAN HEALTH.

column168: DRIVER HAD BEEN TOLD COMPARTMENT SIZE WAS 1500 GALLONS.  THE SIZE WAS ACTUALLY 1400 GALLONS.  WHEN HE TRIED TO PUT 1500 GALLONS IN THE 1400 GALLON COMPARTMENT THE PILL RESULTED.

VALVE BETWEEN COMPARTMENTS WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED AND AS DRIVER WAS FILLING ONE COMPARTMENT PART OF PRODUCT WENT INTO OTHER COMPARTMENT.  WHEN HE TRIED TO FILL THE SECOND COMPARTMENT THERE WAS ALREADY PRODUCT IN IT FROM THE FIRST COMPARTMENT RESULTING IN OVERFILL.

DOCK WORKER NOTICED ONE WET CARTON. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, A PIN HOLE WAS DISCOVERED NEAR THE CAP OF ONE INNER CONTAINER.  DAMAGED CARTON WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY PAIL ALONG WITH ACID NEUTRALIZER.  PAIL WAS SEALED AND FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED DOCK WORKER NOTED TWO DRUMS IN NOSE OF TRAILER LAYING ON THEIR SIDE SHIFTED FORWARD AND OVERTURNED. SHIPPER ADVISED MATERIAL WAS BIODEGRADEABLE AND CLEAN UP INVOLVED WASHING DOWN WITH WATER TO DILUTE.  ONE OF TWO DRUMS HAD APPARENTLY LEAKED AROUNG THE BUNG.

IN ATTENTION OF DRIVER/LOADED WHILE LOADING CARGO TANK ALLOWED TANK TO OVERFLOW.  INLAD STEEL CALLED OUT WATER TRUCK AND FLUSHED THE OVERFLOW INTO THERI WASTE ACID HOLDING AND DISPOSED BASIN, DRIVER HAS BEEN SUSPENDED WHILE INCIDENT IS BEING REVIEWED.  MEMO POSTED FOR ALL DRIVERS LOADING CARGO TANKS TO BE FULLY ALERT AT ALL TIMES DURING LOADING PROCESS.

column168: TANK CAR UTLX 76155 WAS FOUND LEAKING ON ITS UNDERSIDE WHILE LOCATED IN TRACK SY15 AT STACY YARD, SEATTLE, WASHINGTON.  AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY THE CAP HAD EITHER BEEN REMOVED OR HAD FALLEN OFF.

PRODUCT WAS BEING DELIVERED INTO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK WHEN TANK BECOME FULL AND OVERFILLED.  THE STORAGE TANK DID NOT HAVE A LIQUID LEVEL GAUGING DEVICE AND CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL FAILED TO ACCURATELY GAUGE THE HOLDING CAPACITY OF THEIR TANK.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEAN UP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY THE CONSIGNEE.

SHORTLY AFTER COMMENCING THE PRODUCT DELIVERY, A LEAK WAS DETECTED AT A FLANGE IN THE CARGO TANK'S PIPING SYSTEM.  THE DELIVERY WAS STOPPED, THE LEAK WAS TERMINATED AND THE DELIVERY WAS THEN CONCLUDED WITHOUT INCIDENT. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND AND CLEANUP WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL.

column168: LINE DRIVER, WILLIAM D. GRESSETT, AGE 62, WAS DRIVING ON I-20 NEAR RUSTON, LA AT THE FARMERVILLE EXIT AT APPROX 11:00 A.M. ON 4-23-90. HE HEARD AN EXP LOSION AND WHEN CHECKING HIS MIRROR, SAW FLAMES COMING FROM THE REAR TRAILE R. THE TRAILER WAS TOTALLY DESTROYED IN THE RESULTING EXPLOSION AND FIRE. T HE APPROX CAUSE OF THE FIRE WAS THE MIXING OF INCOMPATIBLE CHEMICALS. CONTA INED IN THE SHIPMENT WERE CORROSIVES AND OXIDIZERS. THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDER ED FROM THE FRED B. HIGHT COMPANY IN RALEIGH, NC AND WAS DESIGNATED ON ONE BILL. AS A RESULT, THE DOCKWORKER WHO LOADED THE TRAILER DID NOT RECOGNIZE THE INCOMPATIBILITY AND LOADED THEM SIDE BY SIDE. APPARENTLY DURING TRANSIT THERE WAS LEAKAGE WITH A MIXING OF THE COMMODITIES WHICH CAUSED THE EXPLOS ION AND FIRE. THE RUSTON FIRE DEPT. ALONG WITH ENVIRO-MED LAB OF RUSTON, LA CONTROLLED THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS. A NUMBER OF OTHER COMPANIES INCLUDING ARK ANSAS VACUUM SERVICE AND DIXIE TOWING PARTICIPATED IN THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS. BROWNING-FERRIS INDUSTRIES (BFI) WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR DISPOSAL OF THE TRAIL ER AND COMMODITIES.

HIGHT COMPANY IN RALEIGH, NC AND WAS DESIGNATED ON ONE BILL. AS A RESULT, THE DOCKWORKER WHO LOADED THE TRAILER DID NOT RECOGNIZE THE INCOMPATIBILITY AND LOADED THEM SIDE BY SIDE. APPARENTLY DURING TRANSIT THERE WAS LEAKAGE WITH A MIXING OF THE COMMODITIES WHICH CAUSED THE EXPLOS ION AND FIRE. THE RUSTON FIRE DEPT. ALONG WITH ENVIRO-MED LAB OF RUSTON, LA CONTROLLED THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS. A NUMBER OF OTHER COMPANIES INCLUDING ARK ANSAS VACUUM SERVICE AND DIXIE TOWING PARTICIPATED IN THE CLEAN-UP PROCESS. BROWNING-FERRIS INDUSTRIES (BFI) WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR DISPOSAL OF THE TRAIL ER AND COMMODITIES.

WHILE BEING HANDLED AT DFW FOR OUTBOUND SHIPMENT TO PHEONIX, AZ AN AMERICAN AIRLINES EMPLOYEE NOTICED SMALL ARMS AMMUNITION FALLING FROM A SEAM IN THE CORNER OF ONE OF THE BOXES.  THIS INFORMATION WAS RELAYED TO CARGO SUPERVISOR BURGER WHO SECURED THE SHIPMENT FOR FURTHER INSPECTION. THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN OPENED AND INSPECTED.  ADDITIONAL AMMUNITION WAS FOUND IN BOTH BOXES ALONG WITH VARIOUS TOOLS AND PERSONAL EFFECTS.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED ON MAY 17TH AND THEY INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT ON MAY 18TH. AFTER REMOVING ALL AMMUNITION FROM THE SHIPMENT, FAA INSPECTOR LUSKIE RELEASED THE SHIPMENT FOR TRANSPORT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REPACKAGED AND DEPARTED FOR PHOENIX ON MAY 21ST.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION ON EITHER THE AIRBILL OR THE PACKAGE TO SHOW HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WERE INCLUDED IN THE SHIPMENT ENCLOSED ARE COPIES OF PICTURES TAKEN AT THE TIME OF INSPECTION. AT THE TIME OF DISCOVERY, AMERICAN AIRLINES PERSONNEL TOOK DECISIVE ACTION IN NOTIFYING THE FAA AND NOT PERMITTING THE SHIPMENT TO MOVE TO ITS ULTIMATE DESTINATION.

ON 02/07/90, WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE INSPECTION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENTS AT ALEXANDRIA, LA YARD, MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE GREG PIETRUSZYNSKI AND TROOPER ED BOBBIT OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE OBSERVED PRODUCT EMANATING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR CHVX 280057.  A CLOSER INSEPCTION DETERMINED THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE WAS CONTINOUSLY OPEN. THIS ALLOWED PRODUCT TO SPILL OUT WHEN THE TANK WAS MOVE.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON NOTIFIED.  SSA/HM ROBINSON'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE SPRING IN THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE HAD FAILED AND THAT THE VALVE SHOULD BE REPLACED.  MR. DON FIKE OF CHEVRON WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  MR. FIKE DISPATCHED A NEW VALVE FOR REPLACEMENT.  THE CAR REMAINED AT ALEXANDRIA WITH PIETRUSZYNSKI FACILITATING CHEVRON'S REPLACEMENT OF THE VALVE.  TROPPER BOBBIT MADE THE APPROPRITE NOTIFICATION TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE.
